In `PasswordResetConfirmView` it&#39;s expected that `{{request.user.email}}` won&#39;t work because there&#39;s no authenticated user set on request. `{{request.user}}` will hold an `AnonymousUser` object.

However, if we&#39;re looking at how `PasswordResetConfirmView` is implemented, we&#39;ll notice that in `PasswordResetConfirmView.dispatch()` Django sets the user on `self` like this:

    @method_decorator(sensitive_post_parameters())
    @method_decorator(never_cache)
    def dispatch(self, *args, **kwargs):
        assert &#39;uidb64&#39; in kwargs and &#39;token&#39; in kwargs

        self.validlink = False
        self.user = self.get_user(kwargs[&#39;uidb64&#39;])

This means that you can override `get_context_data()` as you did above and make sure that you&#39;re also sending the user to the template:

    def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):
        context = super(RestorePasswordConfirmView, self).get_context_data(**kwargs)
        context = {**context, **host_(self.request)}
        context[&#39;user&#39;] = self.user
        return context

